VCarnatic instrumental music attracts a large audience, if the artistes adopt a vocalist approach. Instrumental liberties may be taken but should be kept to a bare minimum. Namagiripettai Krishnan, one of the leading Nagaswaram players of his times, h\u000aas presented a soulful and gamaka-oriented display of his talents in this recording brought out by Aditya Music (India) Pvt. Ltd.Krishnan&#8217;s selection of kritis, comprises popular and familiar ones. Tyagaraja&#8217;s &#8216;Thera Theeyagaradha&#8217; (Gowli Pantu) is the opening number. The Vasantha Bhairavi vinyasa is arresting with sancharas and prayogas. &#8216;Nee Daya Radha&#8217; of the saint follows briskly.A brief exposition of Chaya Tarangini precedes Tyagaraja&#8217;s &#8216;Krupa Juchutaku.&#8217; Hindolam is the melody offered on a broad canvas. &#8216;Mamavathu Sri Saraswathi&#8217; (Mysore Vasudevachar) is a bhava rich rendition with a clear understanding of the lyrics.The solfa passages played by Krishnan and K. Murugan culminate in a simple but catchy korvai after the kuraippu.&#8216;Brochevarevarura&#8217; (Khamas ) and the Annamacharya devotional &#8216;Kshirabdi Kanyakagu&#8217; (Kurinji) bring this recording to a good finish. The thavil accompaniment by K. Arumugam and A. Manikandan is good .Nee Daya RadhaAditya Music India P Ltd.Namagiripettai KrishnanNagaswaram &#8212; Audio CDPrice Rs. 99
